VectorClust: Provable Guarantees for Capacity‑Constrained Vector Search

Author: ouadi Maakoul 
---

Abstract

Vector similarity search is a cornerstone of modern AI systems, yet its deployment on heterogeneous hardware clusters introduces critical constraints—memory capacities, latency objectives, and power budgets—that are largely ignored by traditional algorithms. This thesis presents a unified theoretical framework for capacity‑constrained vector search, formalizing it as a capacitated k-clustering problem with a general objective: minimizing any monotone symmetric norm of the per‑vector distances. Such norms capture standard objectives (k-center, k-median, tail quantiles) as well as hybrid metrics.

We adapt the recent FPT approximation framework of [Dai, Li & Peng, 2025] for capacitated minimum‑norm clustering to the domain of vector search, and extend it to handle outliers, multi‑resource capacities, weighted query distributions, and (f,g)-clustering (separate norms for intra‑ and inter‑cluster costs). Our algorithm, VectorClust, runs in time (k\log n/\varepsilon)^{O(k)}\cdot\operatorname{poly}(n) and achieves a (3+O(\varepsilon))-approximation for any monotone symmetric norm. This factor is optimal under standard complexity assumptions (FPT \neq W[1]) for the L_\infty and L_1 special cases, and we conjecture optimality for all such norms.

We provide full, self‑contained proofs for all core lemmas, including a rigorous derivation of the factor 3 via a two‑stage threshold argument. We also give formal treatments of: (i) a static snapshot model for hardware‑aware metrics that preserves the triangle inequality; (ii) a hierarchical routing scheme for federated search with O(\log k) query time overhead; (iii) a coreset reduction that reduces the dataset size to \operatorname{poly}(k,\varepsilon^{-1},\log n) while preserving approximation guarantees.

The thesis establishes a rigorous foundation for capacity‑aware vector search, bridging clustering theory with real‑world deployment constraints. All results are purely mathematical; empirical validation is left for future work.

