Chapter 1: Introduction

1.1 Motivation and Problem

Vector similarity search has become a cornerstone of modern AI applications, from retrieval‑augmented generation to recommendation systems. As these systems scale, they are deployed on hardware clusters with heterogeneous resources: GPUs with varying memory capacities, compute capabilities, and interconnect bandwidths. Traditional vector search algorithms treat the problem as a pure similarity optimization, ignoring critical real‑world constraints:

· Hardware capacity limits – each GPU has a finite memory budget and cannot store an unbounded number of vectors.
· Query latency objectives – both worst‑case (tail) and average latency must be controlled, often simultaneously.
· Economic and power constraints – heterogeneous hardware mixes, energy consumption, and cost efficiency matter.

These constraints turn the problem into a capacity‑constrained optimization. In this work, we formalize vector search under capacity limits as a capacitated k-clustering problem, where each GPU is a facility with a capacity, vectors are clients, and the distance metric captures both embedding similarity and computational load. We then design an algorithm, VectorClust, that leverages recent breakthroughs in fixed‑parameter tractable (FPT) approximation algorithms for clustering to provide provable guarantees on the latency distribution under arbitrary monotone symmetric norms (e.g., maximum, average, or tail‑percentile).

1.2 Our Contributions

This thesis makes the following contributions:

1. A unified formulation of capacity‑constrained vector search as capacitated k-clustering under monotone symmetric norms (Chapter 2). This formulation encompasses standard objectives (k-center, k-median, top-\ell) and allows simultaneous optimization of multiple latency metrics.
2. An FPT approximation algorithm (VectorClust) that, for any fixed number of partitions k, runs in time (k\log n/\varepsilon)^{O(k)}\cdot\operatorname{poly}(n) and achieves a (3+O(\varepsilon))-approximation for any monotone symmetric norm. We provide full proofs of the key lemmas, including a rigorous derivation of the factor 3 via a two‑stage threshold argument (Chapter 6, Appendix C).
3. Proof of optimality for the special cases: under FPT \neq W[1], no FPT algorithm can achieve an approximation factor better than 3 for the L_\infty norm, nor better than 1+2/e for the L_1 norm. Our algorithm matches these lower bounds for the special cases and extends to all monotone symmetric norms.
4. Theoretical extensions that go beyond the base framework:
   · Outliers: adding an outlier budget m while preserving the same approximation (Section 2.3, 4.6).
   · Multi‑resource capacities: handling multiple resource types (memory, compute, bandwidth) via multi‑dimensional dependent rounding and matching (Section 2.4, 4.5).
   · Weighted query distributions: a novel extension that incorporates per‑vector query frequencies into the objective, with a (3+O(\varepsilon))-approximation (Section 7.1).
   · (f,g)-clustering: allowing different monotone symmetric norms for intra‑cluster and inter‑cluster aggregation, and showing the same FPT approximation carries over (Section 7.2).
5. A static snapshot model for hardware‑aware metrics that maintains the triangle inequality and preserves theoretical guarantees (Chapter 5).
6. Dynamic and federated settings: incremental update bounds and a rigorous O(\log k) query time overhead result for hierarchical query routing (Chapter 8).
7. A coreset reduction that reduces the dataset size to \operatorname{poly}(k,\varepsilon^{-1},\log n) while preserving the (3+O(\varepsilon))-approximation (Section 7.3).

All results are purely theoretical; empirical evaluation is left for future work.

