1.4 Related Work

Capacity‑constrained clustering has been studied extensively. Polynomial‑time constant‑factor approximations exist for capacitated k-center [Khuller & Sussmann, 2000] (factor 3) and k-median [Li, 2022] (factor 1+2/e). However, these are not FPT. The recent breakthrough by Dai, Li, and Peng (2025) gave tight FPT approximations for both problems, parameterized by k, and extended the result to any monotone symmetric norm. Their work forms the theoretical foundation for our algorithm.

The (f,g)-clustering framework was introduced by Herold et al. (SODA 2025) and studied for polynomial‑time approximations. Our FPT adaptation is new.

Other lines of work include learning‑augmented indexing (FAISS, HNSW), which provide heuristic solutions without provable guarantees, and systems like DiskANN that optimize for SSD‑based search. These are orthogonal to our theoretical contribution.

Recent work on fair clustering with outliers [Bandyapadhyay et al., 2024] shows that combining capacities and outliers is non‑trivial; our treatment of outliers (Section 2.3) is a direct adaptation of the dummy facility technique used in that paper.

Important concurrent and prior works (2024–2025) directly relevant to our extensions:

· Dabas, Gupta, Inamdar — "FPT Approximation for Capacitated Clustering with Outliers" (TCS, February 2025) [Dabas et al., 2025]. This paper designs the first constant-factor FPT approximation for capacitated k-median with outliers, achieving (3+\varepsilon)-approximation in general metric spaces in time f(k,m,\varepsilon)\cdot|I|^{O(1)}. Our outlier extension (Section 2.3) uses the same dummy‑facility technique and obtains the same guarantee; we now explicitly cite this work as the source of that technique.
· Gadekar & Thejaswi — "Capacitated Fair-Range Clustering" (arXiv:2505.15905, May 2025) [Gadekar & Thejaswi, 2025]. This work designs FPT algorithms for capacitated clustering with both capacity and fairness constraints, achieving (3+\varepsilon) for k-median in FPT(k) time. The fairness constraints are different from our multi‑resource capacities, but both treat non‑scalar constraint structures; the hardness results transfer and we use them to motivate the necessity of FPT.
· Jaiswal, Kumar, Yadav — "FPT Approximation for Capacitated Sum of Radii" (ITCS 2024) [Jaiswal et al., 2024]. This achieves an FPT (3+\varepsilon)-approximation for uniform‑capacitated sum of radii and (4+\sqrt{13})-approximation for non‑uniform capacities, with an ETH‑based hardness lower bound showing super‑FPT hardness for the non‑uniform case. The non‑uniform case maps directly to our heterogeneous GPU capacities scenario, providing evidence that our FPT approach is essentially optimal.
· Bandyapadhyay & Chen — "FPT Approximation for Capacitated k-Median and Sum of Radii with Mergeable Constraints" (APPROX/RANDOM 2025) [Bandyapadhyay & Chen, 2025]. This work obtains a (4+\varepsilon)-approximation for k-MSR with mergeable constraints (including capacities) in time k^{O(\log k)}\cdot n^{O(1)}, offering a different runtime‑approximation tradeoff compared to VectorClust’s (k\log n/\varepsilon)^{O(k)}\cdot\operatorname{poly}(n) bound.

These works are incorporated into the discussion in the relevant sections and listed in the bibliography.

