Chapter 2: Problem Formulation

2.1 Capacitated Clustering for Vector Search

We are given a set of vectors V = \{v_1, \dots, v_n\} \subset \mathbb{R}^d. These vectors represent data points to be partitioned among k facilities (GPUs). Each facility i has a capacity u_i \in \mathbb{N}, indicating the maximum number of vectors it can host. The capacity may be derived from memory limits, compute budgets, or a combination.

A distance function d: V \times V \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} is defined, satisfying the triangle inequality, symmetry, and non‑negativity. In vector search, d often measures dissimilarity between embeddings; we can also incorporate load and hardware characteristics as additive components, provided the resulting function remains a metric (we discuss this in Chapter 5).

The goal is to assign each vector to a facility, respecting capacities, and to minimize an objective that depends on the distances from each vector to its assigned facility’s representative. Formally, let \mu_i be the representative of facility i (for simplicity, we can take \mu_i as one of the vectors assigned to i or a synthetic point; in our algorithm we will treat facilities as points in the metric space). An assignment \sigma: V \to [k] yields distances d(v_j, \mu_{\sigma(v_j)}). We denote the vector of these distances by \mathbf{d} = (d(v_1, \mu_{\sigma(v_1)}), \dots, d(v_n, \mu_{\sigma(v_n)})).

Definition 2.1 (Capacitated k-clustering). Given a set V of clients, a set F of potential facility locations (which may be the same as V), a capacity u_i for each i \in F, and a monotone symmetric norm f, find an assignment \sigma: V \to F with |\sigma^{-1}(i)| \le u_i that minimizes f(\mathbf{d}), where \mathbf{d}_j = d(v_j, \mu_{\sigma(v_j)}).

In our context, the set of facilities is the set of GPUs themselves; we can assume each GPU corresponds to a point in the metric space (e.g., its identifier). For simplicity, we identify each facility with its index i.

2.2 Special Cases

Several well‑known clustering problems are captured by choosing f appropriately:

· k-center: f = L_\infty, i.e., f(\mathbf{d}) = \max_j d_j. This minimizes the maximum distance (worst‑case latency).
· k-median: f = L_1, i.e., f(\mathbf{d}) = \sum_j d_j. This minimizes the total (or average) distance.
· Top-\ell norm: For 0 < \ell \le n,
  \|\mathbf{d}\|_{\text{top-}\ell} = \max_{S \subseteq [n], |S| = \lfloor\ell\rfloor} \sum_{j \in S} d_j + (\ell - \lfloor\ell\rfloor) d_{(\lceil\ell\rceil)},
  where d_{(1)} \ge \dots \ge d_{(n)} are sorted. This focuses on the worst \ell distances (e.g., tail latency).

More generally, any monotone symmetric norm can be expressed as a convex combination of top-\ell norms (Lemma 3.1).

2.3 Outliers

In many practical scenarios, some vectors may be considered “noise” and need not be assigned to any facility, or they may be assigned to a special outlier facility with no capacity limit but incurring a penalty. We extend Definition 2.1 to allow up to m outliers.

Definition 2.2 (Capacitated k-clustering with outliers). Given an additional parameter m (outlier budget), find an assignment \sigma: V \to F \cup \{\bot\} with |\sigma^{-1}(i)| \le u_i for all i \in F and |\sigma^{-1}(\bot)| \le m (where \bot denotes the outlier class), minimizing f(\mathbf{d}) over the assigned points (the distance for outliers is defined as 0, or we can treat them as having infinite distance and exclude them from the norm). Without loss of generality, we may incorporate outliers by adding a dummy facility with infinite capacity and distance 0, but with a penalty in the objective.

Remark. The dummy‑facility reduction is standard for L_1 objectives [Dabas et al., 2025]. For general monotone symmetric norms, we require that setting outlier distances to 0 does not increase the objective. Since f is monotone (componentwise), reducing any component of \mathbf{d} to 0 yields a vector \mathbf{d}' with f(\mathbf{d}')\le f(\mathbf{d}). Therefore the reduction is valid for any monotone symmetric norm.

2.4 Multi‑Resource Capacities

Modern hardware often has multiple resource constraints: memory (number of vectors), compute (e.g., FLOPs), and I/O bandwidth. We model this as a multi‑dimensional capacity vector.

Definition 2.3 (Multi‑resource capacitated clustering). Each facility i has a capacity vector \mathbf{u}_i = (u_i^1, u_i^2, \dots, u_i^r) \in \mathbb{N}^r. Each client j consumes one unit of each resource when assigned to a facility (or more generally, a resource consumption vector \mathbf{w}_j \in \mathbb{N}^r). The assignment must satisfy \sum_{j \in \sigma^{-1}(i)} \mathbf{w}_j \le \mathbf{u}_i coordinate‑wise.

For simplicity, we assume unit consumption per resource; the general case can be reduced by splitting clients into multiple copies.

Hardness note. The multi‑resource variant is at least as hard as multi‑dimensional bin packing, which is strongly NP‑hard even for fixed R. Under ETH, any approximation algorithm for non‑uniform capacitated clustering requires super‑FPT running time [Jaiswal et al., 2024]. Hence, our FPT parameterization by k is essentially necessary.

2.5 Assumptions

We assume the metric space is finite and distances can be computed or approximated efficiently. For the theoretical algorithm, we work with integer distances after scaling and rounding (the standard technique for clustering approximations). We also assume capacities are integral and satisfy \sum_i u_i \ge n (otherwise the instance is infeasible). For the multi‑resource case, we require that the total demand for each resource does not exceed the total capacity.

