Chapter 3: Mathematical Background

3.1 Monotone Symmetric Norms

Let \mathbb{R}^n_{\ge 0} be the set of non‑negative vectors. A function f: \mathbb{R}^n_{\ge 0} \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} is a monotone symmetric norm if it satisfies:

1. Positivity: f(\mathbf{x}) = 0 \iff \mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}.
2. Homogeneity: f(\lambda \mathbf{x}) = \lambda f(\mathbf{x}) for all \lambda \ge 0.
3. Triangle inequality: f(\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{y}) \le f(\mathbf{x}) + f(\mathbf{y}).
4. Monotonicity: If \mathbf{x} \le \mathbf{y} coordinate‑wise, then f(\mathbf{x}) \le f(\mathbf{y}).
5. Symmetry: f(\mathbf{x}) = f(\pi(\mathbf{x})) for any permutation \pi.

Lemma 3.1 (Representation via top-\ell norms). For any monotone symmetric norm f and any \mathbf{x} \in \mathbb{R}^n_{\ge 0}, there exist weights w_1 \ge w_2 \ge \dots \ge w_n \ge 0 such that

f(\mathbf{x}) = \sum_{\ell=1}^n (w_\ell - w_{\ell+1}) \|\mathbf{x}\|_{\text{top-}\ell},

where w_{n+1} := 0. Conversely, any convex combination of top-\ell norms yields a monotone symmetric norm.

Proof. This is a standard fact from the theory of symmetric norms. The set of top-\ell norms forms the set of extreme rays of the cone of monotone symmetric norms. A full proof can be found in [Chakrabarty & Swamy, 2018]. ∎

Thus, approximating f reduces to approximating all top-\ell norms simultaneously.

Definition 3.2 (Top-\ell norm). For \ell \in [0,n],

\|\mathbf{x}\|_{\text{top-}\ell} = \min_{t \ge 0} \left( \sum_{j=1}^n (x_j - t)_+ + \ell t \right),

where (x)_+ = \max\{0, x\}. The optimum is achieved when t equals the \ell-th largest coordinate.

3.2 Fixed‑Parameter Tractability (FPT)

An algorithm is fixed‑parameter tractable with parameter k if its running time is bounded by g(k) \cdot \operatorname{poly}(n), where g is some computable function depending only on k. For clustering, k is the number of clusters (facilities). In vector search, k is typically small (e.g., number of GPUs, often \le 100), making FPT algorithms practical even if the exponential dependence on k is large.

3.3 Hardness of Capacitated Clustering

Theorem 3.3 (Hardness results).

· Capacitated k-center and k-median are NP‑hard for all capacities u_i \ge 2.
· Under the assumption FPT \neq W[1], there is no FPT algorithm achieving approximation factor 3-\varepsilon for capacitated k-center, nor 1+2/e-\varepsilon for capacitated k-median, for any \varepsilon>0.
· These lower bounds extend to the top-\ell norm and any monotone symmetric norm that includes these as special cases.

These results are established in [Dai et al., 2025; Cohen‑Addad et al., 2019] and show that our approximation ratios are optimal for FPT algorithms in the L_\infty and L_1 cases.

