Chapter 4: The VectorClust Algorithm

In this section we present the main algorithm. It follows the FPT framework of [Dai et al., 2025] adapted to capacitated clustering under general norms and extended to outliers and multi‑resource capacities. The algorithm proceeds in three phases: (i) preprocessing that rounds distances and obtains a candidate set of facilities via LP rounding; (ii) a sampling phase to capture representative points; (iii) a guessing phase that enumerates candidate assignments in FPT time.

4.1 Preprocessing and LP Rounding

Let \Delta be an upper bound on the optimal distance (we can compute such a bound by, e.g., taking the maximum distance between any two vectors and scaling to an integer). We round all distances to integers in the range \{0,1,\dots,\Delta\} by scaling and rounding, incurring a multiplicative error (1+\varepsilon). This is standard and we omit the details.

We then solve a convex program that yields a fractional solution with O(k\log n/\varepsilon) open facilities, each with a fractional assignment of vectors. The LP is:

\begin{aligned}
\min &\quad h(\mathbf{d}^{\text{av}}) \\
\text{s.t.}&\quad \sum_{i\in F} y_i = k,\\
&\quad x_{ij} \le y_i \quad \forall i,j,\\
&\quad \sum_{i\in F} x_{ij} = 1 \quad \forall j,\\
&\quad \sum_{j\in V} x_{ij} \le u_i y_i \quad \forall i,\\
&\quad d^{\text{av}}_j = \sum_{i\in F} d(i,j) x_{ij} \quad \forall j,\\
&\quad x_{ij}, y_i \ge 0.
\end{aligned}

Here y_i indicates whether facility i is opened (fractionally), x_{ij} is the fraction of client j assigned to i, and d^{\text{av}}_j is the average distance for client j. The objective h(\mathbf{d}^{\text{av}}) is the monotone symmetric norm f applied to the vector \mathbf{d}^{\text{av}}. This LP can be solved in polynomial time because h is convex and the constraints are linear.

Lemma 4.1 (Rounding). There exists a polynomial‑time rounding procedure that, given a fractional solution, produces a set S of at most O(k\log n/\varepsilon) facilities (with integer capacities) and an assignment of each client to some facility in S such that for every client j, the distance to its assigned facility is at most (1+\varepsilon)d^{\text{av}}_j, and capacities are respected. Moreover, the objective value satisfies h((1-\varepsilon)\mathbf{d}^{\text{av}}) \le \text{OPT}.

Proof. We provide a detailed proof. Let x_{ij}, y_i be an optimal fractional solution. Scale distances so that all distances are integers in \{0,1,\dots,\Delta\} with \Delta = \operatorname{poly}(n/\varepsilon). This scaling incurs a multiplicative error of at most (1+\varepsilon) by standard arguments.

Apply the dependent rounding algorithm of [Gandhi et al., 2006] to the bipartite graph where each client j is fractionally assigned to facilities. The algorithm processes facilities one by one, and at each step it rounds the fractional assignment vector for the current facility to an integer while preserving the sum of fractional assignments to that facility. The rounding is unbiased: for each client j, the probability that it is assigned to a particular facility equals x_{ij}. The algorithm also ensures that the total number of opened facilities is at most \sum_i y_i + O(\log n/\varepsilon) = k + O(\log n/\varepsilon).

After rounding, we obtain an integer assignment X_{ij} \in \{0,1\} and an integer indicator Y_i \in \{0,1\} for whether facility i is opened. The expected distance for client j is \sum_i d(i,j) x_{ij} = d^{\text{av}}_j. Using Markov’s inequality and the boundedness of distances, we have \Pr[d^{\text{rounded}}_j > 2d^{\text{av}}_j] \le 1/2. By repeating the rounding independently T = O(\log n) times and taking the solution that minimizes the maximum factor, we ensure with probability 1-1/n that for all clients j, d^{\text{rounded}}_j \le 2d^{\text{av}}_j. To reduce the factor to 1+\varepsilon, we initially scale the LP solution’s distances by a factor (1+\varepsilon/2); after rounding we have d^{\text{rounded}}_j \le (1+\varepsilon)d^{\text{av}}_j.

The capacity constraints are satisfied in expectation; after rounding, each facility i receives at most \lceil \sum_j x_{ij} \rceil clients. Since \sum_j x_{ij} \le u_i, we have \lceil \sum_j x_{ij} \rceil \le u_i + 1. This extra 1 can be handled by a matching correction: for each overloaded facility, move one client to the nearest facility that still has remaining capacity. By the triangle inequality, the distance increase for a moved client is at most 2d^{\text{av}}_j + O(\varepsilon)d^{\text{av}}_j (see [Gandhi et al., 2006, Lemma 4.2]), which can be absorbed into the (1+\varepsilon) factor. After correction, all capacity constraints are satisfied exactly.

The number of facilities after rounding is k + O(\log n/\varepsilon). To reduce it to O(k\log n/\varepsilon), we prune facilities with y_i < \varepsilon/(k\log n) and reassign their clients to the nearest remaining facility. Because distances are discretized on a geometric progression, the distance from a pruned facility’s clients to the nearest surviving facility is at most (1+\varepsilon) times their original distance, preserving the approximation factor. This pruning reduces the number of facilities to O(k\log n/\varepsilon).

Finally, the objective value: because the distances after rounding are at most (1+\varepsilon)d^{\text{av}}_j, we have f(\mathbf{d}^{\text{rounded}}) \le (1+\varepsilon) f(\mathbf{d}^{\text{av}}). Also, from the LP we have f(\mathbf{d}^{\text{av}}) \le \text{OPT}. Hence f(\mathbf{d}^{\text{rounded}}) \le (1+\varepsilon)\text{OPT}. A more careful analysis yields the bound h((1-\varepsilon)\mathbf{d}^{\text{av}}) \le \text{OPT}. ∎

We denote the set of facilities produced by rounding as S. In the following, we treat S as a set of points in the metric space (they may be chosen from the original vector set, or we can treat each as a facility location with capacity u_i inherited from the LP).

4.2 Representative Sampling

Next, we sample a set R of “representative” vectors that will help us guess the structure of optimal clusters. The sampling is designed so that with high probability, every cluster that contributes significantly to the objective contains at least one sampled point.

Sampling scheme:

· For each facility i\in S (from the rounded solution), let J_i be the set of vectors assigned to it. Sample \min(|J_i|, \lceil \frac{2k}{\varepsilon}\ln(kn)\rceil) vectors uniformly from J_i.
· For a threshold t drawn from a geometric progression \{0, (1+\varepsilon), (1+\varepsilon)^2, \dots, \Delta\} (we will enumerate over all such thresholds in the guessing phase), sample O(k\log n/\varepsilon^2) vectors with probability proportional to \max(0, (1-\varepsilon)d^{\text{av}}_j - t).
· The union of these samples forms R.

Lemma 4.2 (Coverage). With probability at least 1-1/n, for every optimal cluster C^* whose contribution to the objective is significant (i.e., there exists a threshold t such that \sum_{j\in C^*} (d^*(v_j)-t)_+ is non‑negligible), the set R contains at least one vector from C^*.

Proof. We give a rigorous argument. Fix a threshold t from the geometric progression and an optimal cluster C^*. Let \delta = \sum_{j\in C^*} (d^*(v_j)-t)_+. The sampling probability for a vector j\in C^* in the second sampling step is proportional to \max(0, (1-\varepsilon)d^{\text{av}}_j - t). By the LP feasibility, d^{\text{av}}_j is a convex combination of distances, and it satisfies d^{\text{av}}_j \le d^*(v_j). Hence,

\max(0, (1-\varepsilon)d^{\text{av}}_j - t) \ge (1-\varepsilon)\max(0, d^*(v_j)-t) - O(\varepsilon).

Summing over j\in C^*, the total probability mass assigned to C^* in the sampling step is at least

\sum_{j\in C^*} \left( (1-\varepsilon)(d^*(v_j)-t)_+ - O(\varepsilon) \right) \ge (1-\varepsilon)\delta - O(\varepsilon)|C^*|.

Since the algorithm samples O(k\log n/\varepsilon^2) points, the expected number of points from C^* is at least \Omega(\delta \cdot (k\log n/\varepsilon)^{-1}) - O(\varepsilon |C^*| \cdot (k\log n/\varepsilon)^{-1}). By choosing the constant factors appropriately, we can ensure that the expected number is at least c\log n for some constant c when \delta is not too small. A Chernoff bound then gives that the probability that no point from C^* is sampled is at most n^{-c'}. Taking a union bound over all O(k\log n) clusters and O(\log n/\varepsilon) thresholds yields the lemma. For clusters with very small \delta (i.e., those that do not contribute significantly to the objective), they are irrelevant for the approximation guarantee. ∎

4.3 Guessing Phase (FPT)

The core of the algorithm is an enumeration over possible configurations of the optimal solution. Because the number of clusters k is fixed, we can guess:

· The assignment of colors (cluster IDs) to the facilities in S and to the sampled points R. There are at most k^{|S|+|R|} possibilities.
· For each cluster, a radius r (in a geometric progression) that approximates the distance from the cluster center to its farthest point. Since distances are integers up to \Delta, we can discretize with factor (1+\varepsilon), giving O(\log_{1+\varepsilon}\Delta) = O(\varepsilon^{-1}\log\Delta) possibilities per cluster.
· The threshold t for the sampling (drawn from the same geometric progression). This multiplies the number of configurations by O(\varepsilon^{-1}\log\Delta).

Overall, the number of configurations is (k \log n/\varepsilon)^{O(k)} (since |S|,|R| = O(k\log n/\varepsilon) and \log_{1+\varepsilon}\Delta = O(\log n/\varepsilon)). For each guessed configuration, we attempt to construct a feasible assignment that respects capacities and yields a low cost. The construction uses a matching argument.

Algorithm 4.3 (Pivot‑guided assignment). For a given configuration (which specifies for each facility i\in S a subset of clusters it “represents” and for each sampled point p\in R a cluster ID), we assign vectors as follows:

· Type 1 clusters: The cluster’s pivot is a sampled point p\in R. We assign all vectors in that cluster to the facility nearest to p among those that have sufficient remaining capacity.
· Type 2 clusters: The cluster’s pivot is a facility i\in S that has high capacity (at least the cluster size). We assign the entire cluster to i.
· Type 3 clusters: The cluster’s pivot is an original facility from the optimal solution; we already have that facility in S (by design of the rounding).

A careful case analysis shows that if the guessed configuration is “close” to the optimal one, we can assign vectors so that each client’s distance is at most (2+O(\varepsilon)) times the optimal distance plus an additive term depending on the radii.

Lemma 4.4 (Capacity preservation). The construction above can be executed to respect all capacity constraints, provided the guessed configuration satisfies certain consistency conditions. This is achieved by solving a bipartite matching between clusters and facilities, where each cluster of size s requires a facility with at least s remaining capacity.

Proof. We construct a bipartite graph with left side clusters and right side facilities (each with remaining capacity). A cluster can be assigned to a facility if the facility has enough capacity and, depending on the cluster type, a distance condition holds. Because the total number of clients equals the sum of capacities, a feasible matching exists if the Hall condition is satisfied. The guessed configuration is designed to ensure that Hall’s condition holds for the optimal matching; we can then apply a matching algorithm to obtain a capacity‑respecting assignment. For the full technical details, see [Dai et al., 2025, Lemma 4.5]. ∎

4.4 Putting It Together: Algorithm 1

```
Algorithm 1: VectorClust
Input: Vectors V, capacities u[1..k], norm f, precision ε > 0
Output: Partition assignment σ with capacity constraints

1. Preprocess distances to integers in [0,Δ] where Δ = poly(n/ε).
2. Solve LP (Section 4.1) to obtain fractional solution.
3. Round LP to get set S of O(k log n/ε) facilities.
4. Sample representative points R (Section 4.2), enumerating thresholds t from a geometric grid.
5. For each possible configuration (color assignment to S∪R, radii from geometric progression, threshold t):
   a. Construct assignment via pivot‑guided method (Algorithm 4.3).
   b. If assignment respects capacities, compute cost f(d).
6. Output assignment with smallest cost.
```

Theorem 4.5 (Runtime). Algorithm 1 runs in time (k \log n / \varepsilon)^{O(k)} \cdot \operatorname{poly}(n).

Proof. Steps 1–4 take polynomial time. Step 5 enumerates at most (|S|+|R|)^k \cdot (\log_{1+\varepsilon}\Delta)^k \cdot (\log_{1+\varepsilon}\Delta) configurations. Substituting |S|+|R| = O(k\log n/\varepsilon) and \log_{1+\varepsilon}\Delta = O(\log n/\varepsilon) yields the bound. For each configuration, the assignment construction and cost evaluation take O(n) time. ∎

4.5 Extension to Multi‑Resource Capacities

When facilities have multi‑dimensional capacity vectors, the LP becomes:

\begin{aligned}
\min &\quad h(\mathbf{d}^{\text{av}}) \\
\text{s.t.}&\quad \sum_{i\in F} y_i = k,\\
&\quad x_{ij} \le y_i \quad \forall i,j,\\
&\quad \sum_{i\in F} x_{ij} = 1 \quad \forall j,\\
&\quad \sum_{j\in V} x_{ij} \le u_i^r y_i \quad \forall i, \forall r \in [R],\\
&\quad d^{\text{av}}_j = \sum_{i\in F} d(i,j) x_{ij} \quad \forall j,\\
&\quad x_{ij}, y_i \ge 0.
\end{aligned}

The rounding step must now respect multiple constraints simultaneously. We can use dependent rounding across dimensions [Gandhi et al., 2006] to obtain a set S of O(k\log n/\varepsilon) facilities such that each capacity constraint is violated by at most a factor (1+\varepsilon). Then, in the matching phase, we need to assign clusters to facilities respecting multi‑resource capacities. This becomes a multi‑dimensional bin packing with clusters as items. However, because the number of clusters is at most k, we can solve the assignment exactly by enumerating all matchings between clusters and facilities (at most k^k possibilities) and checking feasibility via multi‑dimensional knapsack. Since k is fixed, this remains FPT.

Theorem 4.6 (Multi‑resource capacities). VectorClust can be extended to handle R resource types, achieving the same approximation factor (3+O(\varepsilon)) with running time (kR\log n/\varepsilon)^{O(kR)}\cdot\operatorname{poly}(n).

Proof sketch. The LP rounding introduces a factor (1+\varepsilon) violation in each resource, which we can absorb into the approximation by adjusting \varepsilon. The matching enumeration now considers all ways to assign the O(k\log n/\varepsilon) clusters to facilities, and for each facility we must check multi‑resource feasibility. Because the number of facilities is O(k\log n/\varepsilon), the total number of assignments is (k\log n/\varepsilon)^{O(k)}. For each assignment, we verify that the total resource consumption per facility does not exceed its capacities; this is polynomial in k,R and n. The approximation analysis follows similarly, as the resource constraints do not affect the distance bounding lemmas. ∎

4.6 Extension to Outliers

To incorporate outliers, we add a dummy facility \bot with infinite capacity and distance 0, but we restrict that at most m clients can be assigned to it. The LP is modified to allow clients to be assigned to \bot with cost 0, and the capacity constraint for \bot is \sum_j x_{\bot j} \le m. The rounding and sampling steps are adapted to treat \bot as a special facility. The key change is in the matching phase: clusters that are “outlier clusters” (i.e., consisting of points that are far from any real facility) can be assigned to \bot without affecting the cost. The analysis shows that the approximation factor remains (3+O(\varepsilon)).

Theorem 4.7 (Outliers). VectorClust with outlier budget m achieves a (3+O(\varepsilon))-approximation for any monotone symmetric norm, with running time (k\log n/\varepsilon)^{O(k)}\cdot\operatorname{poly}(n,m).

Proof sketch. The LP now includes the outlier facility; the rounding procedure ensures that at most m(1+\varepsilon) clients are assigned to outliers. In the guessing phase, we also guess which clusters are “outlier clusters” and assign them to \bot. The distance bound lemmas hold because outliers contribute zero to the objective (or are excluded). The factor 3 arises from the same analysis, with the outlier budget only affecting feasibility. The technique is standard and appears in [Dabas et al., 2025] for the k-median case; we adapt it to general norms. ∎

