Chapter 7: Further Theoretical Extensions

7.1 Weighted Query Distributions

In practice, not all vectors are queried equally often; popular vectors should have lower latency. We introduce a weighted monotone symmetric norm that incorporates query frequencies.

Definition 7.1 (Weighted top-\ell norm). Let w_1, \dots, w_n \ge 0 be weights with \sum_j w_j = 1. Define

\|\mathbf{x}\|_{w\text{-top-}\ell} = \min_{t \ge 0} \left( \sum_{j=1}^n w_j (x_j - t)_+ + \ell t \right).

A weighted monotone symmetric norm is any convex combination of such weighted top-\ell norms.

This captures the idea that the tail latency for the \ell most weighted points matters. The weights can be proportional to query frequency.

Theorem 7.2 (Weighted approximation). VectorClust can be adapted to achieve a (3+O(\varepsilon))-approximation for any weighted monotone symmetric norm, with the same FPT runtime.

Proof sketch. The adaptation is straightforward: in the LP, replace the objective with h(\mathbf{d}^{\text{av}}) where h is the weighted norm. In the sampling phase, sample points with probability proportional to w_j \max(0, (1-\varepsilon)d^{\text{av}}_j - t). The rest of the algorithm remains unchanged. The threshold lemma (Lemma 6.1) generalizes to weighted sums using the same case analysis, because the weights factor out of the triangle inequality. The top-\ell norm proof then carries over with the weighted sum. ∎

7.2 (f,g)-Clustering

In many applications, we may want to first compute a cost per cluster (e.g., maximum distance, sum of distances) and then aggregate these cluster costs using another norm. This is captured by the (f,g)-clustering framework [Herold et al., 2025].

Definition 7.3 ((f,g)-clustering). Given an assignment \sigma, let \mathbf{c}_i be the vector of distances from points in cluster i to its center. Define the cluster cost as g(\mathbf{c}_i), and then the overall cost is f((g(\mathbf{c}_1),\dots,g(\mathbf{c}_k))), where f and g are monotone symmetric norms.

Our earlier formulation corresponds to the special case where g is the identity (or top-\ell norm) and f aggregates over points. The VectorClust algorithm can be adapted to handle any (f,g) where both f and g are monotone symmetric norms. The key is to modify the LP to reflect the cluster cost g. Because the number of clusters k is small, we can enumerate all possible ways to assign clusters to facilities and, for each cluster, compute its cost using g. The same FPT guessing technique works.

LP modification. To incorporate g, we note that g can be expressed as a convex combination of top-\ell norms: g(\mathbf{x}) = \sum_{\ell=1}^{|C|} w_\ell \|\mathbf{x}\|_{\text{top-}\ell}. For each cluster i, we introduce auxiliary variables z_{i\ell} that represent the \ell-th largest distance in that cluster. The constraints

\sum_{j \in \text{cluster } i} (d_j - z_{i\ell})_+ \le (\ell-1) z_{i\ell} \quad \text{and} \quad \sum_{j \in \text{cluster } i} (d_j - z_{i\ell})_+ \ge (\ell-1) z_{i\ell}

can be linearized using standard techniques for top-\ell norms (see [Dai et al., 2025]). Since k is fixed, the total number of such auxiliary variables is O(kn), and the LP remains polynomial in n. The rounding and sampling steps then proceed as before, treating each cluster’s cost g(\mathbf{c}_i) as an aggregated value that is monotone in the individual distances. The approximation factor 3+O(\varepsilon) carries over because the threshold lemma applies to the aggregated costs as well. For a detailed treatment, we refer to [Herold et al., 2025].

Theorem 7.4 (Approximation for (f,g)-clustering). There exists an FPT algorithm that, for any monotone symmetric norms f,g, achieves a (3+O(\varepsilon))-approximation for capacitated (f,g)-clustering with running time (k\log n/\varepsilon)^{O(k)}\cdot\operatorname{poly}(n).

Proof sketch. The algorithm is similar to VectorClust but with the LP extended to include the auxiliary variables representing g(\mathbf{c}_i). The rounding and sampling steps remain unchanged; the guessing phase now includes the cluster costs. The distance bounding lemmas extend because the cluster cost is monotone in the distances. The full details are provided in [Herold et al., 2025, Section 4]. ∎

7.3 Coresets for Capacitated Clustering

A coreset is a small weighted subset of the input that approximates the clustering cost for any possible set of centers. Formally, a set C \subseteq V with weights w: C \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} is an \varepsilon-coreset if for every set of k centers F, the weighted sum of distances from C to F is within a factor (1\pm\varepsilon) of the sum from the original dataset.

Theorem 7.5 (Existence of coresets). For capacitated clustering with monotone symmetric norm objectives, there exists an \varepsilon-coreset of size \operatorname{poly}(k, \varepsilon^{-1}, \log n).

Proof. The sensitivity sampling framework of Braverman et al. [2016] applies because monotone symmetric norms can be expressed as convex combinations of top-\ell norms, each of which has bounded sensitivity. Specifically, for each top-\ell norm, the sensitivity of a point is at most O(k \ell / n) in the capacitated setting; a union bound over the n top-\ell components yields a total sensitivity O(k \log n). Applying the sensitivity sampling theorem gives a coreset of size O(k \varepsilon^{-2} \log^2 n). The capacity constraints can be handled by a reduction to unweighted clustering via duplication of points, but care must be taken to avoid blowing up the dataset size. A more efficient approach uses the fact that the sensitivity of a point is bounded by a function of its distance to the optimal centers; this remains true even under capacities [Cohen‑Addad & Li, 2024]. The resulting coreset size is \tilde{O}(k^2 \varepsilon^{-2} \log n) for k-median; for general norms, the bound becomes \operatorname{poly}(k, \varepsilon^{-1}, \log n) by applying the representation lemma. ∎

Using a coreset, we can first reduce the dataset size to O(k\varepsilon^{-2}\log n) and then run VectorClust on the coreset, obtaining the same approximation guarantees in time (k\log n/\varepsilon)^{O(k)}\cdot \operatorname{poly}(k,\varepsilon^{-1},\log n).

Remark on Euclidean spaces. In constant‑dimensional Euclidean spaces, stronger approximations are possible. For example, Dabas et al. [2025] achieve a (1+\varepsilon)-approximation for capacitated k-median with outliers using coresets. Extending such results to general monotone symmetric norms in Euclidean spaces is an open direction.

