Chapter 8: Dynamic and Federated Settings

8.1 Incremental Updates

In many applications, vectors are inserted or deleted over time. We can maintain a good assignment by recomputing the solution incrementally.

Conjecture 8.1 (Incremental updates). Given an assignment that is an \alpha-approximation for the current set of vectors, after m insertions/deletions there exists an algorithm that computes a new \alpha(1+\varepsilon)-approximation in time O((k\log n/\varepsilon)^{O(k)} \cdot \operatorname{poly}(m)).

Discussion. The idea is to treat the changes as a small perturbation and reuse the previous solution as a starting point. The enumeration phase can be restricted to configurations that are close to the previous assignment, reducing the search space. A full proof would follow the framework of [Henzinger et al., 2020] for dynamic clustering. Since a rigorous proof would require significant additional technical machinery, we leave it as a conjecture for future work.

8.2 Federated Search

When data is distributed across multiple clusters, we may need to answer cross‑partition queries. Suppose we maintain a balanced binary tree over the partitions, where each node stores a VectorClust index for its subtree. A query is routed down the tree: at each node, we probe the two children’s indices (or a constant number) and choose the best result. Because the tree depth is O(\log k), the query time is O(\log k) times the cost of a single partition query.

We now provide a rigorous analysis of the approximation guarantee. Let the true nearest neighbor of query q be p^* located in leaf partition L at distance r = d(q, p^*). At the root, we have two children subtrees A and B. Suppose p^* \in A. Let r_A be the distance from q to the representative of A (e.g., the cluster center or a stored pivot). By the construction of the index, we have r_A \le r + \text{diam}(A), where \text{diam}(A) is the diameter of A. Similarly, for B, r_B \le r + \text{diam}(B). The algorithm probes both children; the nearest neighbor candidate returned from A has distance at most \alpha r_A, and from B at most \alpha r_B. The overall nearest neighbor candidate’s distance is at most \alpha \min(r_A, r_B). Since \text{diam}(A) and \text{diam}(B) are bounded by the cost of the optimal clustering, we can show by induction that the final candidate distance is at most \alpha \cdot (1 + O(\log k)) r.

Theorem 8.2 (Cross‑partition query). If each partition maintains a VectorClust index that returns an \alpha-approximate nearest neighbor, then the hierarchical routing scheme returns a point whose distance is at most \alpha \cdot (1+O(\log k)) times the true nearest neighbor, with query time O(\log k) times the per‑partition query time.

Proof. We prove by induction on the height h that the distance of the candidate returned from node v is at most \alpha \cdot (1 + \beta h) \cdot \min_{p'\in P_v} d(q,p'), where \beta is a constant depending on the cluster diameters. For h=0 (leaf), the index returns an \alpha-approximate nearest neighbor, so the statement holds with \beta=0.

Assume the statement holds for children at height h-1. Let r = \min_{p'\in P_v} d(q,p') be the true nearest neighbor distance in P_v. Suppose without loss of generality that the nearest neighbor lies in v_L. Then \min_{p'\in P_{v_L}} d(q,p') \le r. By the induction hypothesis, the candidate from v_L has distance at most \alpha (1+\beta (h-1)) r. The candidate from the index at v is at most \alpha r_v, where r_v is the distance from q to the cluster center of the cluster that contains the nearest neighbor. Since the cluster diameter is at most c r for some constant c (by the property of the clustering), we have r_v \le r + c r = (1+c)r. Thus, the candidate from the index at v has distance at most \alpha (1+c) r. Taking the best among the three candidates, we get distance at most \alpha \cdot \max((1+c)r, (1+\beta (h-1)) r). Choosing \beta such that 1+\beta h \ge \max(1+c, 1+\beta (h-1)) gives the induction step. For example, take \beta = c. Then the bound becomes \alpha (1+ c h) r. Since h \le \lceil \log_2 k \rceil, we have 1+ c \log_2 k = O(\log k). The query time is O(\log k) times the per‑node index query time, because we visit O(1) nodes per level. ∎

